  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering is a serious crime with significant penalties. Generally, a person convicted of money laundering can face:\n\n1. Criminal Penalties:\n- Imprisonment up to 20 years\n- Substantial financial fines\n- Criminal forfeiture of assets involved in transactions\n\n2. Specific Penalties:\n- Transactions over $10,000: Up to 10 years in prison\n- Transactions designed to avoid reporting requirements: Up to 5 years\n- Repeat offenses can result in enhanced sentences\n\n3. Additional Consequences:\n- Asset seizure\n- Potential civil penalties\n- Professional license revocation\n- Significant damage to personal and professional reputation\n\n4. Sentencing Factors:\n- Amount of money involved\n- Sophistication of the laundering scheme\n- Prior criminal history\n- Role in the offense\n\nThese penalties are typically established under the Money Laundering Control Act and enforced by federal agencies like the Department of Justice. Specific penalties can vary based on the exact nature and circumstances of the offense.\n\nNote: This information is general legal overview and should not be considered specific legal advice. Consulting a qualified attorney is recommended for detailed guidance.",
